<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>‘What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS007</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Alexandra Payling </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?’</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Department of Politics</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The University of Sheffield</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary: </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">An alternative to </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> that should be offered to failing primary schools is one where the Department for Education (</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">) and Local Authorities (LAs) focus a commitment of resources to reduce class sizes and improve levels of professional development. This would enable an increased level of </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">individualised</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> teaching which is also </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">utilised</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">parts of </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">East Asia and Canada, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">which have internationally </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hi</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">gh outcomes in educational attainment</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. Smaller classes will </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">improve results</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> in core areas like reading, writing and mathematics. It also allows more time to incorporate activities which improve creativity, physical and mental health. This alternative model of cl</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ass size reduction would raise</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> school and pupil achievement levels in an inter-connected process because:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Reducing class sizes from current standards of 30 pupils to lower levels of 15 would model excellence in the education provision demonstrated internationally. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Smaller class sizes would give teachers the time for weekly continued professional development.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Increased professional development would enable teachers to develop and own strategies for pupil and teaching improvement designed in a SMARTER framework (specific, measurable, achievable, realistic, time, exciting, and recorded). This should be in collaboration alongside key stakeholders like the LA/</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> and parents to ensure there is communication and accountability of teachers to headteachers and HR.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Since 2010, the academy conversion has cost in excess of £8 billion and has resulted in the siphoning of funds that should have gone to assist underperforming schools.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> Many of the conversions were from schools already rated by Ofsted as good or outstanding. This does not represent good value for money in improving the education of low and middle range pupil attainment levels in failing primary schools and it increases inequalities.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Academy status does not guarantee success for a failing primary school and its pupils. In 2013, nationally maintained primary schools achieved a higher proportion of pupils who attained level 2B and 3 in Key Stage 1 than those in sponsored academies. </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Many conversions to academy status have occurred without parental support and in spite of progress that failing schools have made. This has been the case at Snaresbrook primary in South Woodford, a failing school where parents are campaigning against the </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> attempt to push it into academy status as reported in September 2013.  A lack of accountability or consultation with parents in changes to educational provision reduces their ability to scrutinise the proposals and have their voices heard. This infringes on their moral and legal responsibility under the Child Act 1989 to ensure their children receive an adequate education. It reduces their ability to participate in decisions about their children’s education where the responsibility has been outsourced to the state in lieu of the right to home educate.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">A reduction in class size is more appropriate for failing primary schools than </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> programmes as it addresses multiple factors that can influence student behaviour and attainment inside and outside the classroom. It would give greater time for teacher professional development and engagement with parents. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">This would produce a micro-level self-improving system which could take ownership and accountability for the design and implementation of improvement plans for subsequent students and their individual learning needs. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">These plans would be in conjunction with the headteacher and the LA with the financial support from the </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> to give teachers the support they identify is necessary to ensure each child reaches their optimum potential.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Diversity of Attainment and Learning Needs</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">A study of pupils at the end of year one in 2013 found that: 66% met the standard of 32/40 marks in phonics and national curriculum assessment. This is positive and is an increase since 2012 with a reduction in the number of pupils who scored below 30. There has been improvement across the current primary school system as a whole but there are still inequalities between children.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">In 2013 there were variations between pupils who achieved the national standard score: Indian (80%), Chinese (77%), black (71%), white (69%), black Caribbean (66%), Traveller-Irish (28%), Gypsy/Roma(23%). A lower percentage was obtained by pupils who are eligible for free school meals (56%) and girls performed 10% higher than boys within this category. The proportion of pupils with and without a SEN statement who achieved the expected standard was 32% with those with a hearing for visual impairment achieving the highest proportion of the expected standard scores.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">A failing primary school will need additional resources if it is oversubscribed by children who fall in the categories which are shown to attain lower scores across the country. Smaller class sizes and individualised teaching would benefit students who have significantly lower than average learning outcomes</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> A school will perform better, not necessarily due to better teaching, but because it has lower levels of pupils from known underperforming ethnicities, free school meals eligibility or SEN. The bias in admissions needs to be taken into account when league tables are used as a judgement of a schools success or failure and a system of blind lottery style admissions should be considered as used in charter schools in California.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Research on year groups 3, 4, 5 and 6 shows that higher numbers of pupils achieved no progress or regressed in the summer to autumn term which is possibly related to the summer holidays.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> Research shows that “</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">fewer than 800 pupils make progress </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">continuously </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">in writing through years 4 to 6”.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">This is important to consider when making assessments of a school’s speed of improvement but also shows that individualised teaching methods at first entry could have a significant impact to improving the numbers who make continuous progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Ofsted reported that teachers should utilise a high level of interaction throughout lessons. This is less likely to occur in a class of 30 especially considering that four in ten children in the population of primary pupils are not considered secure in their English skills.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> In a smaller class teachers would have more time to check pupils work and go over areas of difficulty until they are mastered.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A Reduction in Class Size and not </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Academisation</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">As the amount of failing schools is relatively small overall, just under 5%, there is no reason for systemic change. Maintained schools are doing comparably better than academy conversions. The average size of classes is within the legal limit of 30 but the largest distribution of pupils is within classes of 30 pupils. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">In 2013, the best performing schools tended to have a smaller number of pupils in the year.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Smaller numbers would allow for a more individualized and child-centered approach to education and would give teachers the time they need for professional development. This alternative is based on models </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">of primary education policy in Alberta, Canada. Recognised as having a world class education provision, the Alberta provincial government recommends that class size for year 3 and below should have a ratio of 17 to 1 pupils to qualified teachers. This type of policy would have support from teachers and parents in failing primary schools. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">It would improve the likelihood that every parent sends their child to a </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">local </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">school which maintains excellence in practice to reach the optimal level of academic and personal development for </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">every </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">pupil.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">By investing in additional qualified teachers, class sizes could be reduced which would build on the example of success shown in Alberta where the learning and family culture is more similar to the UK’s than that in East Asia.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Time for Professional Development</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Smaller class sizes is key to the turnaround of a failing primary school but it needs to be incorporated alongside the weekly professional development of teachers and intra-school communication. Andreas Schleicher, who runs the PISA exam, attributed China’s improvements to the time allowed for professional development which is in contrast to a style seen in the USA and the UK where teaching, lesson plans and marking take up most of a teacher’s day.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Shanghai’s excellence in educational provision is linked to the time (20% of the working week) they have for learning innovative teaching practice and having peer-to-peer assessments.  Continued professional development would enable headteachers, with the support of HR, to identify success and failures and to ensure that teaching staff are held to account for the delivery of the highest levels of teaching reinforced by ongoing training.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Smaller Class Sizes and Attainment</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Many of the top countries in the international education league tables recognise that class size can affect pupil outcomes positively if implemented at the beginning of their education. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">DfEs</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> own findings show that smaller class sizes are linked to improvements in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> and attainment by pupils.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Research shows a strong relationship between smaller class sizes, improved behaviour of pupils and pupil/teacher interaction across all attainment levels which can impact learning outcomes positively especially for low and middle achievers.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">When class sizes increases off-task behaviour increases for low and middle achievers. In addition, the proportion of time a teacher spends on managing negative behaviour increases for pupils who are low and middle achievers. Peer to peer off-task behaviour increased with larger classes and the amount of pupil/teacher individual attention and interaction decreased for all pupils when class size increased.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Research from Sweden also shows that smaller class sizes in the final years of primary school have long-term effects which outweigh the costs. There was increased achievement at age 16 and increased wages and earnings at ages 27 and 42.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">An investment in additional qualified teaching staff to reduce class sizes is an investment that pays dividends and would be an effective alternative for failing primary schools instead of </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. A reduction in class size alone is not enough and a Shanghai approach is recommended by the incorporation of teacher’s continuous professional development, and ensuring a respect for the professional standing of teachers as a competitive career choice. Smaller classes allow for more </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">individualised</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> teaching to improve pupil attainment.  It would improve equality of access for parents and pupils to a local and outstanding education provision and is a more appropriate and efficient alternative than </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> to deliver results.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">HoC</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">Public Accounts Committee ‘41</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:5.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> Report-Department for Education: Managing the Expansi</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">on of the Academies Programme’, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">UK PARLIAMENT, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">15 April 201</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">3, Para. 3,4).</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">‘http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmpubacc/787/78705.htm (accessed 12.12.2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">Department for Education ‘ Phonics screening check and national curriculum at Key Stage 1 in England:2013- Key Stage 1 National Table’ , Table 10. ( </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">UK, Parliament, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt">12 December 2013) </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/phonics-screening-check-and-national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-1-in-england-2013"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/gover</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">n</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">ment/publications/phonics-screening-check-and-national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-1-in-england-2013</span></a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> (accessed 13.12.2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:8pt"> Department fo